Step 1 — Update the Pi
bashsudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

Step 2 — Install system dependencies
bashsudo apt install -y python3-pip python3-venv libopenblas-dev
sudo apt install -y python3-picamera2

Step 3 — Create and activate venv
bashcd ~/Queue-Predictor-IoT
python3 -m venv venv --system-site-packages
source venv/bin/activate

--system-site-packages is important on Pi — it lets the venv access picamera2 which is installed system-wide


Step 4 — Install PyTorch for Pi (ARM version)
bashpip install torch torchvision --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cpu

This takes a while on Pi — 10-20 minutes is normal


Step 5 — Install ultralytics
bashpip install ultralytics

Step 6 — Enable the camera
bashsudo raspi-config
Go to Interface Options → Camera → Enable, then reboot:
bashsudo reboot

Step 7 — Test camera works
bashpython3 -c "from picamera2 import Picamera2; cam = Picamera2(); cam.start(); print('Camera ok'); cam.stop()"

Step 8 — Test YOLO works
bashpython3 -c "from ultralytics import YOLO; model = YOLO('yolov8n.pt'); print('YOLO ok')"

Step 9 — Run the people counter
bashpython hardware/vision/people_counter.py

The Pi 4 is slow with YOLO but for a 2 second polling interval it's fine — it just means the Pi will be busy during detection but idle between readings.